"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/50164","Department for Education","false","2014-05-14","<p>The total number of students funded in 2012/13 in school sixth forms, academy sixth forms and 16-19 free schools established since September 2011 was 9,610 and the total actual number of students enrolled was 7,775. The numbers by institution type are as follows:</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Institution Type</p></td><td><p>2012/13 Funded Students</p></td><td><p>2012/13 Actual Students</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Academy</p></td><td><p>5276</p></td><td><p>4152</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>16-19 Free School</p></td><td><p>220</p></td><td><p>197</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>School Sixth Form</p></td><td><p>4114</p></td><td><p>3426</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Total</p></td><td><p>9610</p></td><td><p>7775</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>The majority of academies and all maintained schools are funded on a lagged basis so that numbers recruited in one year will then determine the allocation in the following year.Some academies are funded on the basis of estimated numbers, and their funding is then adjusted based on actual recruitment. The impact on sixth form funding of any such adjustments is included in these figures.</p><p>The approximate total net cost of unfilled places in respect of the above in 2012/13 was £5.76 million. Institutions with unfilled places will have their funding reduced in the following year. The costs by institution type are as follows:</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Institution Type</p></td><td><p>Net Cost of Unfilled Places</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>SSF</p></td><td><p>£3.24 million</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Academy</p></td><td><p>£2.39 million</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>16-19 Free School</p></td><td><p>£0.13 million</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Total</p></td><td><p>£5.76 million</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p>","Surrey Heath","Michael Gove","198072","2014-05-14T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/50164/answer","Biography information for Michael Gove","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/50164/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/50164/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2014-05-07",,"1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what advance estimate he made of the number of students enrolled in (a) school sixth forms, (b) academy sixth forms and (c) 16 to 19 years free schools estabished since September 2011 in 2012-13; and what the number of students was in each case.","false","Biography information for Kelvin Hopkins","Luton North","Kelvin Hopkins","198071"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/50165","Department for Education","false","2014-05-14","<p>The total number of students funded in 2012/13 in school sixth forms, academy sixth forms and 16-19 free schools established since September 2011 was 9,610 and the total actual number of students enrolled was 7,775. The numbers by institution type are as follows:</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Institution Type</p></td><td><p>2012/13 Funded Students</p></td><td><p>2012/13 Actual Students</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Academy</p></td><td><p>5276</p></td><td><p>4152</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>16-19 Free School</p></td><td><p>220</p></td><td><p>197</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>School Sixth Form</p></td><td><p>4114</p></td><td><p>3426</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Total</p></td><td><p>9610</p></td><td><p>7775</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>The majority of academies and all maintained schools are funded on a lagged basis so that numbers recruited in one year will then determine the allocation in the following year.Some academies are funded on the basis of estimated numbers, and their funding is then adjusted based on actual recruitment. The impact on sixth form funding of any such adjustments is included in these figures.</p><p>The approximate total net cost of unfilled places in respect of the above in 2012/13 was £5.76 million. Institutions with unfilled places will have their funding reduced in the following year. The costs by institution type are as follows:</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Institution Type</p></td><td><p>Net Cost of Unfilled Places</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>SSF</p></td><td><p>£3.24 million</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Academy</p></td><td><p>£2.39 million</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>16-19 Free School</p></td><td><p>£0.13 million</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Total</p></td><td><p>£5.76 million</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p>","Surrey Heath","Michael Gove","198071","2014-05-14T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/50165/answer","Biography information for Michael Gove","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/50165/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/50165/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2014-05-07",,"1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what the cost was of student places that were not filled in (a) school sixth forms, (b) academy sixth forms and (c) 16 to 19 free schools estabished since September 2011 in 2012-13.","false","Biography information for Kelvin Hopkins","Luton North","Kelvin Hopkins","198072"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/50166","Department for Education","false","2014-05-12","<p>Sixth-form colleges are classified as private sector institutions and already benefit from the freedoms that academies enjoy. For this reason, the Department for Education has no plans to publish guidance for sixth-form colleges that wish to convert to become 16 to 19 academies.</p><p> </p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Mr Edward Timpson",,"2014-05-12T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/50166/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/50166/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/50166/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2014-05-07",,"1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, when his Department will publish guidance for sixth form colleges that wish to convert to become 16 to 19 academies.","false","Biography information for Kelvin Hopkins","Luton North","Kelvin Hopkins","198073"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/50167","Ministry of Defence","false","2014-05-12","<p>The £35 million LIBOR fund has now closed with the majority of the money being allocated in support of a total of 97 projects. A copy of the document detailing those projects and the funding they have received is attached. A small sum is being held back for contingencey purposes.</p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2014-05-12T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/50167/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/50167/answer","20140508-PQN 13-14 2014-01264 Attachment-Successful LIBOR Projects.xls","20140508-PQN 13-14 2014-01264 Attachment-Successful LIBOR Projects.xls","Libor fund","Libor fund","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/50167/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2014-05-07",,"1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, if he will provide details of the projects supported by the Armed Forces Covenant (LIBOR) Fund since its inception; and how much funding has been given to each of those projects.","false","Biography information for Vernon Coaker","Gedling","Vernon Coaker","198149"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/50168","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2014-05-12","<p> </p><p> </p><p>The Government are aware of the problems facing young jobseekers in the labour market and have put in place a substantial menu of provision to help them move into work.</p><p>The Youth Contract provides intensive support for all 18-24 year olds. Extra funding is being made available to support the most vulnerable 16 and 17 year olds not in education, employment or training into learning, an apprenticeship or job with training.</p><p> </p><p>This comprehensive package of support is enhanced by the Flexible Support Fund, which Jobcentre Plus District managers can use to address locally identified skills needs. Also, the Work Programme provides tailored support to those claimants furthest from the labour market.</p><p> </p><p>Additionally, on the 14<sup>th</sup> of November, the Deputy Prime Minister announced that funding of £50m Youth Contract under spend would be made available to cities.</p><p>For the Sheffield City Region they received £5m to offer intensive adviser and mentor-led support for young people alongside a specialist training programme aimed at equipping young people with the right skills to match local employer needs.</p>","Wirral West","Esther McVey",,"2014-05-12T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/50168/answer","Biography information for Esther McVey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/50168/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/50168/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2014-05-07",,"1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what steps he is taking and what budget he has allocated to help tackle youth unemployment in (a) Barnsley and (b) South Yorkshire.","false","Biography information for Dan Jarvis","Barnsley Central","Dan Jarvis","198129"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/50169","Department of Health","false","2014-05-12","<p>This information is not available in the format requested. The hon. Member may wish to contact Yorkshire Ambulance Service NHS Trust, who may hold data at a more local level.</p><p> </p><p>The following table shows median ambulance response times for Yorkshire Ambulance Service NHS Trust in the latest three months for which figures are available.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td colspan="2"><p><strong> </strong></p><p>Yorkshire Ambulance Service NHS Trust</p><p> </p><p>Median response times (minutes) for Category A calls</p><p><strong> </strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p><p>January 2014</p></td><td><p> </p><p>5.5</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p><p>February 2014</p><p> </p></td><td><p> </p><p>5.7</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p><p>March 2014</p></td><td><p> </p><p>5.6</p><p> </p></td></tr></tbody></table><p><strong> </strong></p><p><em>Source</em>: Ambulance quality indicators, NHS England</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p><em>Note:</em></p><p>Response time shown is for Category A (Red) calls. These are defined as those that are the result of immediately life threatening incidents.</p><p><strong><em> </em></strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2014-05-12T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/50169/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/50169/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/50169/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2014-05-07",,"1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what ambulance response times were in each local authority area in the Yorkshire and the Humber region in the latest period for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Dan Jarvis","Barnsley Central","Dan Jarvis","198043"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/50170","Ministry of Defence","false","2014-05-14","<p>This winter's severe weather and consequent flooding represented a significant test of the nation's civil resilience framework and demonstrated the effectiveness of military contingency planning. The Ministry of Defence (MOD) was able to generate a 5,000-strong taskforce and engage our specialist capabilities to fill gaps without detrimental impact to operations or significant training disruption. The MOD continues to plan against a broad range of civil emergencies in support of wider Government contingency planning.</p>","Rayleigh and Wickford","Mr Mark Francois",,"2014-05-14T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/50170/answer","Biography information for Mr Mark Francois","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/50170/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/50170/answer","Rayleigh and Wickford","Mr Mark Francois","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/50170/answer/previousversion/9753","Biography information for Mr Mark Francois","11","Defence","Defence","2014-05-07",,"1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what operational contingency plans he has made for future capability requirements in the event of further flooding.","false","Biography information for Dan Jarvis","Barnsley Central","Dan Jarvis","198125"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/50171","Cabinet Office","false","2014-05-12","<p>The information requested falls within the responsibility of the UK Statistics Authority. I have asked the Authority to reply.</p><p> </p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2014-05-12T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/50171/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/50171/answer","PQ 198130.pdf","PQ 198130.pdf","Jobs Created - ONS Letter","Jobs Created - ONS Letter","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/50171/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2014-05-07",,"1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many new jobs have been created in (a) 2011, (b) 2012 and (c) 2013 in (i) Barnsley central constituency, (ii) Yorkshire and the Humber and (iii) England.","false","Biography information for Dan Jarvis","Barnsley Central","Dan Jarvis","198130"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/50172","Ministry of Justice","false","2014-05-12","<p> </p><p> </p><p>Manslaughter has a maximum penalty of life imprisonment. Whilst sentence lengths for manslaughter have increased by almost 50% since 2008 there remains clear public concern about the sentences imposed in so called “one punch” manslaughter cases.</p><p> </p><p>Clarification of the sentencing of these difficult cases would assist the courts and be helpful to the public. The Secretary of State therefore wrote to Lord Justice Treacy, the Chair of the Sentencing Council on 8 May 2014, to make a formal request that the Council gives consideration to producing guidance on the sentencing of these cases.</p>","Kenilworth and Southam","Jeremy Wright",,"2014-05-12T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/50172/answer","Biography information for Jeremy Wright","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/50172/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/50172/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2014-05-07",,"1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, if he will invite the Sentencing Council to consult and report on the adequacy of current sentences available for killing with one punch.","false","Biography information for Nick de Bois","Enfield North","Nick de Bois","198154"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/50173","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2014-05-14","<p> </p><p>Melissococcus plutonius is the causative agent of European foulbrood. In 2012 the Dutch reported the results of a survey that used sensitive detection methodologies to suggest a 35 percent apiary prevalence of Melissococcus plutonius across the Netherlands.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>But a 2012-13 pan-European epidemiological study on honey bee colony losses found a low prevalence of European foulbrood across 15 Member States:</p><p> </p><p><a href="http://ec.europa.eu/food/animals/live_animals/bees/docs/bee-report_en.pdf" target="_blank">http://ec.europa.eu/food/animals/live_animals/bees/docs/bee-report_en.pdf</a>.</p><p> </p>","North Cornwall","Dan Rogerson",,"2014-05-14T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/50173/answer","Biography information for Dan Rogerson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/50173/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/50173/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2014-05-07",,"1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what evidence there is of contamination of the bacterial pathogen, Melissoccocus plutonius, from countries within the EU.","false","Biography information for Simon Reevell","Dewsbury","Simon Reevell","198102"
